-- tCoda: Scepticism and the Spectacular – On Shakespeare in an Age of Science -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the interaction between science, literature and spectacle in Shakespeare’s eraTo the readers who ask themselves: ‘What is science?’, this volume provides an answer from an early modern perspective, whereby science included such various intellectual pursuits as history, poetry, occultism and philosophy. By exploring particular aspects of Shakespearean drama, this collection illustrates how literature and science were inextricably linked in the early modern period. In order to bridge the gap between Renaissance literature and early modern science, the essays collected here focus on a complex intellectual territory situated at the point of juncture between humanism, natural magic and craftsmanship. It is argued that science and literature constantly interacted, thus revealing that what we now call ‘literature’ and what we choose to describe as ‘science’ were not clear-cut categories in Shakespeare’s days but rather a part of common intellectual territory.Key FeaturesAnalyses different aspects of Shakespeare’s plays through the prism of early modern science Sheds fresh light on major works such as the Sonnets, Love’s Labour’s Lost, Romeo and Juliet, Twelfth Night, King Lear, Hamlet, Othello, Macbeth, The Tempest, The Winter’s TaleCombines theoretical views, historical approaches, and close readingsOffers an innovative dialectic vision of the Shakespeare/science nexus, taking up Mazzio’s seminal idea that it is now necessary to move beyond forms of analysis focused largely on thematic traces of, or indeed linguistic reflections of, historically specific arenas of scientific practice" Links science and spectacle and posits that early modern theatre fashioned the reception of early modern discoveriesPays attention to systems of thought which bind together scientific and literary discourses, practices and mentalities within a single episteme (in Michel Foucault’s interpretation of the word)"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLiterature and science. 0aSciencexHistoryy16th century. 0aSciencexHistoryy17th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh1 aCampos, Liliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiari, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDulac, Anne-Valérie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIselin, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones-Davies, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapitaniak, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaroque, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLejri, Sélima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLestringant, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazzio, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPopelard, Mickaël, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPopelard, Mickaël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442783840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474427838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474427838/original  a978-3-11-078140-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aE